    <h1>First stop HTML basics!</h1>
    <p><strong> What is Html?</strong></p>
    <p>Html stand for <em> HyperText Markup Language</em>. It's The basic Structure of every website you see!</p>
    <h2>An Html Page Structure</h2>
    <p>Every Html page has a basic structure that looks like this:</p>
    <pre>
&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;
&lt;html lang="en"&gt;
    &lt;head&gt;
        &lt;meta charset="UTF-8"&gt;
        &lt;meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0"&gt;
        &lt;title&gt;Page Title&lt;/title&gt;
    &lt;/head&gt;
    &lt;body&gt;
        &lt;h1&gt;Hello World!&lt;/h1&gt;
        &lt;p&gt;This is my first HTML page.&lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;/body&gt;
    </pre>
    <p>Let's break it down:</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;</strong>: This tells the browser that this is an HTML5 document.</li>
        <li><strong>&lt;html lang="en"&gt;</strong>: The root element of the HTML document, with a language attribute.</li>
        <li><strong>&lt;head&gt;</strong>: Contains meta-information about the document, like character set and title.</li>
        <li><strong>&lt;body&gt;</strong>: Contains the content of the page that users see, like headings and paragraphs.</li>
</body>
        <li><strong>&lt;h1&gt;</strong>: A top-level heading, used for the main title of the page.</li>
        <li><strong>&lt;p&gt;</strong>: A paragraph element, used for blocks of text.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Now you know the basic structure of an HTML page!</p>
    <p>Next, let's learn about some common HTML elements.</p>   
    <h2>Common HTML Elements</h2>
    <p>Here are some common HTML elements you will use:</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>&lt;a&gt;</strong>: Anchor element for links. Example: <code>&lt;a href="https://example.com"&gt;Visit Example&lt;/a&gt;</code></li>
        <li><strong>&lt;img&gt;</strong>: Image element. Example: <code>&lt;img src="image.jpg" alt="Description"&gt;</code></li>
        <li><strong>&lt;ul&gt;</strong> and <strong>&lt;ol&gt;</strong>: Unordered and ordered lists. Example: 
            <pre>
&lt;ul&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;Item 1&lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;Item 2&lt;/li&gt;     
    &lt;li&gt;Item 3&lt;/li&gt; 
&lt;/ul&gt;
            </pre>
        </li>
        <li><strong>&lt;div&gt;</strong>: A generic container for grouping elements. Example: <code>&lt;div class="container"&gt;Content&lt;/div&gt;</code></li>
        <li><strong>&lt;span&gt;</strong>: An inline container for text. Example: <code>&lt;span style="color: red"&gt;Red Text&lt;/span&gt;</code></li>
        <li><strong>&lt;form&gt;</strong>: Used for creating forms. Example: 
            <pre>   
&lt;form action="/submit" method="post"&gt;



    &lt;label for="name"&gt;Name:&lt;/label&gt;
    &lt;input type="text" id="name" name="name"&gt;
    
    &lt;label for="email"&gt;Email:&lt;/label&gt;
    &lt;input type="email" id="email" name="email"&gt;
    
    &lt;input type="submit" value="Submit"&gt;
&lt;/form&gt;
            </pre>
        </li>   
        <li><strong>&lt;table&gt;</strong>: Used for creating tables. Example: 
            <pre>   
&lt;table&gt;

    &lt;tr&gt;
        &lt;th&gt;Header 1&lt;/th&gt;
        &lt;th&gt;Header 2&lt;/th&gt;
    &lt;/tr&gt;
    &lt;tr&gt;
        &lt;td&gt;Row 1, Cell 1&lt;/td&gt;
        &lt;td&gt;Row 1, Cell 2&lt;/td&gt;
    &lt;/tr&gt;
    &lt;tr&gt;
        &lt;td&gt;Row 2, Cell 1&lt;/td&gt;
        &lt;td&gt;Row 2, Cell 2&lt;/td&gt;
    &lt;/tr&gt; 
&lt;/table&gt;
            </pre>
        </li>
        <li><strong>&lt;header&gt;</strong>, <strong>&lt;footer&gt;</strong>, <strong>&lt;nav&gt;</strong>: Semantic elements for page structure. Example: 
            <pre>   
&lt;header&gt;  

    &lt;h1&gt;Page Header&lt;/h1&gt;        
    &lt;nav&gt;
        &lt;a href="#home"&gt;Home&lt;/a&gt;
        &lt;a href="#about"&gt;About&lt;/a&gt;
        &lt;a href="#contact"&gt;Contact&lt;/a&gt;  
    &lt;/nav&gt;